<div class="wrapper">
  <h1>// OS Core Concepts</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">KERNEL ¬∑ MEMORY ¬∑ FILESYSTEM ¬∑ DRIVERS ¬∑ BOOT</p>

  <div class="split">
    <div class="split-pane kernel">
      <div class="pane-label k">‚öôÔ∏è KERNEL SPACE <span class="ring-badge">RING 0 ¬∑ PRIVILEGED</span></div>
      <div class="pane-desc">The core of the OS. Has <strong style="color:#00d4ff">full access to hardware</strong>. Manages system calls ‚Äî requests from software to the OS. Operates in privileged mode. A bug here can compromise the entire system.</div>
      <div style="margin-top:10px"><span class="tag">full hardware access</span><span class="tag">syscall handler</span><span class="tag">trusted</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">Minimising kernel attack surface is critical</div>
    </div>
    <div class="split-pane user">
      <div class="pane-label u">üë§ USER SPACE <span class="ring-badge">RING 3 ¬∑ RESTRICTED</span></div>
      <div class="pane-desc">Where applications run in a <strong style="color:#ff6b9d">restricted environment</strong>. Processes are isolated from each other ‚Äî one app cannot read another's memory. Must request hardware access via syscalls to the kernel.</div>
      <div style="margin-top:10px"><span class="tag">isolated processes</span><span class="tag">restricted access</span><span class="tag">syscall requests</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">Process isolation prevents lateral movement</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="divider-arrow">‚Üë syscall boundary ‚Äî user space cannot cross without kernel permission ‚Üë</div>

  <div class="concepts">
    <div class="card" style="--c:#a78bff">
      <div class="card-title">Process &amp; Memory Management</div>
      <div class="card-desc">The OS schedules CPU time slices across processes and manages virtual memory through paging and segmentation ‚Äî each process gets its own isolated address space mapped to physical RAM.</div>
      <div style="margin-top:8px"><span class="tag">paging</span><span class="tag">segmentation</span><span class="tag">virtual memory</span><span class="tag">CPU scheduling</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">ASLR ¬∑ NX Bit ¬∑ Stack Canaries protect this layer</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="--c:#7fff7f">
      <div class="card-title">Filesystems &amp; I/O</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Filesystems abstract physical storage into files and directories. The OS enforces permissions (rwx), Access Control Lists (ACLs), and Mandatory Access Controls via SELinux or AppArmor. Encrypted filesystems add confidentiality.</div>
      <div style="margin-top:8px"><span class="tag">ACLs</span><span class="tag">SELinux</span><span class="tag">AppArmor</span><span class="tag">encryption</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">DAC + MAC = layered access control</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="--c:#ffdd57">
      <div class="card-title">Device Drivers &amp; Modules</div>
      <div class="card-desc">Drivers run with kernel-level privileges, making them high-value attack targets. Modern OSes mitigate this through driver signing (cryptographic verification), sandboxing, and loading modules only when needed.</div>
      <div style="margin-top:8px"><span class="tag">kernel privileges</span><span class="tag">driver signing</span><span class="tag">sandboxing</span><span class="tag">modular loading</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">Unsigned drivers = untrusted code in Ring 0</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="--c:#ff9500">
      <div class="card-title">Boot &amp; Firmware</div>
      <div class="card-desc">The boot process initialises hardware then loads the OS kernel. UEFI Secure Boot cryptographically verifies each step in the chain ‚Äî firmware ‚Üí bootloader ‚Üí kernel ‚Äî ensuring only signed, trusted binaries execute.</div>
      <div style="margin-top:8px"><span class="tag">UEFI</span><span class="tag">Secure Boot</span><span class="tag">chain of trust</span><span class="tag">TPM</span></div>
      <div class="security-note">Prevents bootkits and firmware-level rootkits</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
